The paper presents a framework for molecule optimization using deep reinforcement learning techniques, specifically double Q-learning and randomized value functions. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves the modification of molecules, which is a task related to chemical engineering (cs.CE). The use of domain knowledge of chemistry also suggests that the paper may belong to the computational chemistry (cs.CL) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the optimization of molecules, which may involve image processing techniques (cs.CV) to visualize the path through chemical space.
